  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Plant stanol esters as part of daily diet can decrease serum level of LDL-cholesterol up to
      10%. This decrease diminishes the risk of development of premature atherosclerosis and it´s
      complications (e.g., acute myocardial infarction) in adult human subjects.

      The purpose of the present study is to evaluate among healthy human subjects (N=100) effects
      of plant stanol esters (3 grams/day for 6 months) as part of daily diet in margarine on
      arterial endothelial cells, arterial stiffness, autonomic innervation of the arteries,
      arterial blood flow and serum fats. The non-invasive arterial measurements (VaSera®, EndoPat®
      and WinCRPS®) are performed and blood samples are taken at the beginning and at the end of
      the 6-month-long study period. Also questionnaires concerning healthy, and life and dietary
      habits are fulfilled. Dietary records (twice for a 3-day-period) are done.

      Hypothesis of the study is that a dietary serum cholesterol lowering intervention has
      beneficial influence on the early prognostic markers of premature atherosclerosis.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
